snippet.textDisplay:
16:40 The Clear/Soft section was a bit inaccurate. You can easily be high-contrast but Soft. I am. And I definitely look bad in Clear colors. Colors that are dark and muted/soft work my skin.

19:40 Changing your hair color does NOT change your Soft/Clearness. It can change your contrast level. Or it can just look wrong if you choose the wrong color. Kristen Stewart does not automatically become Clear if she dyes her hair black. She is a Soft Summer.

Overall, thanks for this video. More people should think about color theory.
snippet.textOriginal:
16:40 The Clear/Soft section was a bit inaccurate. You can easily be high-contrast but Soft. I am. And I definitely look bad in Clear colors. Colors that are dark and muted/soft work my skin. 

19:40 Changing your hair color does NOT change your Soft/Clearness. It can change your contrast level. Or it can just look wrong if you choose the wrong color. Kristen Stewart does not automatically become Clear if she dyes her hair black. She is a Soft Summer.

Overall, thanks for this video. More people should think about color theory.

snippet.textDisplay: There are some other things to mention: neutral skin tones exist, too, there's not only warm and cool, neutral ones can basically wear any undertone...silver, gold and warm/cool colours. Haircolor, Make-up and confidence also play a role in my opinion. I also think that there are some light (pastel) colors that look great on dark skin but really bad on fair skin. In the end, I would say yes you can definitely look better with the right colours matching your skin, hair, make-up and character but wear what you want as long as you feel confident and good wearing it, even if the color doesn't suit you, if it's your favourite color and you feel great wearing it, just do it :-).
